==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*īsarna-'', probably from Celtic ''*īsarno-''.  Cognates include Old Saxon [[isarn|īsarn]] (Dutch [[ijzer]]), Old High German [[isarn|īsarn]] (German [[Eisen]]), Old Norse [[isarn|ísarn]] (Swedish [[jårn]]), Gothic [[𐌴𐌹𐍃𐌰𐍂𐌽]], Old Irish ''īärn'' (Irish [[iarann]], Welsh [[haearn]]).  The Celtic source was related to Latin [[aes]] ‘bronze’.

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'i:zern/

===Noun===
'''īsern''' ''n'' (''pl'' '''īsern''')
# the metal [[iron]]
# an instrument or tool made from iron, especially an iron [[sword]]
# an iron [[shackle]] or [[fetter]]

===Adjective===
'''īsern'''
# consisting or made of [[iron]]

